<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-04-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-04-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="126" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d126">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">819.415C/–</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Panama</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">South</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Panama</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-04-02"><hi rend="italic">April 2,
                                1925</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received April 14.]</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 678</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to transmit herewith a
                            copy with translation of a note just received from the Minister for
                            Foreign Affairs<note n="53" xml:id="d126fn53">Not printed; see Republica
                                de Panama, <hi rend="italic">Congreso Pan-Americano commemorativo
                                    del de Bolívar 1826–1926</hi> (Panama, Imprenta Nacional, 1927),
                                p. 17.</note> inviting the United States Government to be
                            represented by delegates at a Congress which will be held in this city
                            on June 18, 1926, in celebration of the first centennial of the Bolívar
                            Congress of 1826.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">J. G. South</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>